         </item-info>
         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="fig0005">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0005">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0005" view="all">Natural range of <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> with 47 study locations. Locations span 6° latitude and 11 counties from Curry in extreme southwestern Oregon to Monterey in central California. Original <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> distribution is shown in red (compiled by R. Van Pelt from available sources). Locations identified by number and correspond with <ce:cross-ref id="cr0005" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0010" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>, and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0015" refid="sec0135">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>. See Fig. 1 in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0020" refid="bib71">Sillett et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref> for additional detail including panels for elevation, rain, and summer fog. <ce:bold>Appendix A</ce:bold> provides descriptions of locations.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0005" role="short">Fig. 1</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0005" locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr1"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0010">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0010" view="all">Crossdating categories for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> rings and trunk-averaged radial increment for corresponding segment. Diagrams (upper) and images (lower) show crossdating categories and scanned cores from four heights (tree 50, location <ce:bold>10</ce:bold>). Series span 1910–2010; decades marked by single dots, 1950 by two dots, and 2000 by three dots. Black boxes in lower right represent 1 mm<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>, and diagramed rings are proportional to measurements. Shared marker years colored blue, missing rings noted in parentheses. Top series (73 m) has all rings dated with high confidence. Rings colored red are undated (i.e., not annually resolved) but bound, or bracketed, by dated rings. Rings colored orange are dated with moderate confidence due to possibility of alternate location of missing rings. Not shown is category for undated and not bound, where inner rings are not bracketed by dated rings. Bottom panel shows trunk-averaged radial increment (specific volume increment, SVI, mm yr <ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup>) for corresponding segment compiled from 45 series along main trunk including four displayed. Note mid-century section of reduced growth corresponds with small, missing, and undated rings.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0010" role="short">Fig. 2</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0010" locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr2"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0015">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">Chronology length and signal strength for 47 locations across <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> native range. Chronology length has overlays of dark blue when EPS ≥ 0.75 and replication &gt; one tree, light blue when EPS &lt; 0.75 or replication drops to one tree, and red when replication drops to one series. Chronologies listed by latitude from north to south.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0015" role="short">Fig. 3</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0015" locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr3"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0020">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Relationships among 32 location chronologies used for generation of regional and sub-regional chronologies for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in primary forests. a) Pearson’s correlations among chronologies and their relationship with Euclidean distance. Shared variance (100 x <ce:italic>R</ce:italic>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) is shown for pairwise correlations. Matrix shows locations by latitude with darker line separating north and south, and scatterplot has colors denoting pairs by regions. b) Relative positions for first two principal components of 32 chronologies with variance explained in parentheses. c) Regional and sub-regional chronologies with associated sample depth and EPS. Regional indices are for northern (&gt; 40° N) and southern (south of San Francisco Peninsula) portions of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> distribution with sub-regional indices for 41–42°, 40–41°, Santa Cruz Mountains, and Santa Lucia Mountains. Indices truncated at &lt; two or three trees.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0020" role="short">Fig. 4</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0020" locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr4"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0025">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0025" view="all">Response curves for crossdating metrics of 122 <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in relation to key predictors identified by nonparametric multiplicative regression. Trees are currently dominant or co-dominant in primary forests. Two predictors (tree age, DTB) influence undated but bound rings, and three predictors (tree age, heartwood volume, latitude) influence missing rings (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0025" refid="tbl0020">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>). Cross-validated correlations (x<ce:italic>R</ce:italic>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>) for individual predictors are shown.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0025" role="short">Fig. 5</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0025" locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr5"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0030">
               <ce:label>Fig. 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">Frequency of undated rings in relation to trunk-averaged radial increment, or specific volume increment (SVI), for 28 <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> with challenging crossdating. Bars show mean ± 1 SE. Differences between categories determined by exact post hoc test for all pairwise comparisons of Friedman rank sums. Categories not connected by same letter are significantly different (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> ≤ 0.05).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0030" role="short">Fig. 6</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0030" locator="gr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr6"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0035">
               <ce:label>Fig. 7</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0035" view="all">Differences in crossdating metrics by sample height for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in primary forests. Dependent variables are percent undated rings, percent missing rings, interseries correlation, and mean ring width (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0030" refid="tbl0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>). Height categories include 1.4 m (BH) and 10-m increments from 10 to 70 m. Each dependent variable has two complementary analyses: 1.4–70 m (right) and 10–50 m (left). Tree replication shown in upper corner per panel with mean number of years in common period in parentheses. Bars show mean ± 1 SE. Differences between heights determined by exact post hoc test for all pairwise comparisons of Friedman rank sums. Categories not connected by same letter are significantly different (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> ≤ 0.05).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0035" role="short">Fig. 7</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0035" locator="gr7" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr7"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="fig0040">
               <ce:label>Fig. 8</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cap0040">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0040" view="all">Crown structures, running crossdating levels, and biomass increments for ten <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> &gt; 1000 yr old. a) Crown models of trees sequenced by latitude with size, age, and growth metrics; tree number above model. Main trunks (black) and segmented appendages (red) portrayed as conic frustra using measured end diameters and based on direct tree measurements. Crowns depicted as green ellipses showing crown depth and average crown spread. b) Crossdating levels with tree number in upper left corner. In top panels, uppermost value represents all series sampled, red represents series not crossdated (both bound and unbound), orange represents series crossdated with moderate confidence, and gray represents series crossdated with high confidence. For bottom panels, biomass increment (kg yr<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup>) is multiple of trunk wood volume increment extending as far back as dendrochronology allowed. Note variations for X and Y axes. Red arrows indicate top break events dated via series above and below reiterated trunks.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:alt-text id="at0040" role="short">Fig. 8</ce:alt-text>
               <ce:link id="lk0040" locator="gr8" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/gr8"/>
            </ce:figure>
