               <ce:legend>
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0050" view="all">Sections and associated figures, tables, and text are highlighted in bold with regard to five main research questions: (1) What is the signal strength of crossdated <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronologies across its native range? (2) Based on shared variation, how can location chronologies be combined into robust regional and subregional chronologies? (3) To what degree is crossdating success related to variation in tree size and age, landscape position, and growth increment? (4) Where is crossdating success maximized along the trunk height gradient? (5) How does whole-trunk sampling overcome obstacles and present opportunities for dendrochronological analysis of old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>? Text components correspond to headings and sub-headings of Introduction, Methods, Results, and Discussion. Analyses and associated sample details shown in italics. For forest type, P = primary, S = secondary. For crown class, D = dominant, C = co-dominant, I = intermediary, S = subordinate. *Case studies directly address Question 5 and illustrate points relevant to Question 3.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:legend>
            </ce:table>
