                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
               <ce:legend>
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0090" view="all">Unreplicated, complete block design is used with tree as blocking variable. Dependent variables are percent undated rings, percent missing rings, interseries correlation, and mean ring width. Height categories include 1.4 m (BH) and 10-m increments from 10 to 70 m. Each dependent variable has two analyses: 1.4–70 m and 10–50 m. A common period is maintained per tree, whose mean duration is shown along with range in parentheses. DF = degrees of freedom, and χ<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> = Friedman chi-squared test statistic. All tests are statistically significant (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.0001).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:legend>
            </ce:table>
         </ce:floats>
         <head>
            <ce:dochead id="doc0005">
               <ce:textfn>Original article</ce:textfn>
            </ce:dochead>
            <ce:title id="tit0005">Overcoming crossdating challenges to generate ring-width chronologies for <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> across its native range</ce:title>
            <ce:author-group id="ag0005">
               <ce:author id="au0005" author-id="S1125786523000139-329586a69db200746044b7edafec868c">
                  <ce:given-name>Allyson L.</ce:given-name>
                  <ce:surname>Carroll</ce:surname>
                  <ce:cross-ref id="cr0035" refid="cor1">
                     <ce:sup loc="post">⁎</ce:sup>
                  </ce:cross-ref>
                  
               </ce:author>
               <ce:author id="au0010" author-id="S1125786523000139-c56da890f864b85d6e941ed7f47a3660">
                  <ce:given-name>Stephen C.</ce:given-name>
                  <ce:surname>Sillett</ce:surname>
               </ce:author>
               <ce:affiliation id="aff0005" affiliation-id="S1125786523000139-d271146beab217ff6e15fe6c5b8b9c3e">
                  <ce:textfn>Department of Forestry, Fire, and Rangeland Management, Cal Poly Humboldt, Arcata, CA 95521, USA</ce:textfn>
                  <sa:affiliation>
                     <sa:organization>Department of Forestry, Fire, and Rangeland Management, Cal Poly Humboldt</sa:organization>
                     <sa:city>Arcata</sa:city>
                     <sa:state>CA</sa:state>
                     <sa:postal-code>95521</sa:postal-code>
                     <sa:country>USA</sa:country>
                  </sa:affiliation>
                  <ce:source-text id="srct0010">Department of Forestry, Fire, and Rangeland Management, Cal Poly Humboldt, Arcata CA 95521, USA</ce:source-text>
               </ce:affiliation>
               <ce:correspondence id="cor1">
                  <ce:label>⁎</ce:label>
                  <ce:text>Corresponding author.</ce:text>
               </ce:correspondence>
            </ce:author-group>
            <ce:date-received day="31" month="10" year="2022"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="19" month="1" year="2023"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="27" month="1" year="2023"/>
            <ce:abstract id="ab0010" class="author" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="abs0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0095" view="all">We utilize a large dendrochronological dataset for <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> of 1.29 million rings from 5952 series for 278 trees to generate location and regional ring-width chronologies and to investigate constraints on crossdating. Increment cores were collected at regular height intervals along the trunk via free-hanging ropes with some terrestrial deadwood sampled. Inter-annual chronologies span 86–1687 yr for 47 locations in primary and secondary forests across the native <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> range. Shared signals based on declining strength of paired correlations with distance, strong correlations within regions, and groupings of principal components guide chronology creation for northern (1032 yr, 108 trees) and southern (865 yr, 52 trees) regions and four sub-regions. The suite of chronologies provides location-specific references as well as more robust regional indices that reflect distinct signals along a climatically-integrative latitudinal gradient. Secondary forests date to near completion, and we use a subset of data to assess crossdating for trees in primary forests. Among tree and landscape attributes, old age is the most important predictor of undated and missing rings, and undated rings align with periods of reduced biomass production distributed across centuries-long lifespans. Crossdating metrics vary by height above the ground with breast height (BH) and 10 m samples having more undated rings than upper samples. At 10 m, samples have the most missing rings. Buttressing affects the lower trunk as BH series have higher ring widths and lower interseries correlations compared to those up to 70 m. Whole-trunk sampling maximizes success for crossdating old, structurally-complex <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> and enables dating of crown damage and assessment of biomass dynamics related to environmental change. Reference chronologies, regional assessments, and crossdating insights collectively guide future study of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> for applications including climatology, fire ecology, and seismology.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            
            <ce:keywords id="keys0005" class="keyword" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="key0005">
                  <ce:text>Coast redwood</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0010">
                  <ce:text>Dendrochronology</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0015">
                  <ce:text>Crossdating</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0020">
                  <ce:text>Missing rings</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="key0025">
                  <ce:text>Height gradient</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0020">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Raw ring width measurements for crossdated series available in Supplementary Table S1.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec0005" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">
                     <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> is a prime candidate for dendrochronological study due to its extreme size (up to 116 m tall and 400 Mg biomass) and age (up to 2340 yr; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0040" refid="bib66">Sillett et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), but its propensity for anomalous growth rings presents challenges for crossdating and generating reference chronologies (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0005" refid="bib26 bib12">Fritz, 1940; Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-refs>). The native distribution of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> spans 740 km from southwestern Oregon to central California (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0005"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0045" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>) with ∼5% of primary (old-growth) forests remaining (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0050" refid="bib11">Burns et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Globally, old trees are rare with only 30 species documented &gt; 1000 yr (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0055" refid="bib39">Liu et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) and ten &gt; 2000 yr (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0060" refid="bib57">RMTRR, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). High-longevity species occupy a range of biomes (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0065" refid="bib53">Piovesan and Biondi, 2021</ce:cross-ref>) but often occur in high-elevation, cool, dry environments near ecological margins where resources are relatively scarce and growth rates are slow (e.g., <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic>), unlike tall trees that generally occur in more mesic and productive locations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0070" refid="bib39">Liu et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) with small seasonal temperature variations (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0075" refid="bib36">Larjavaara, 2014</ce:cross-ref>). A closely related species also capable of exceeding 90 m tall and 2000 yr, <ce:italic>Sequoiadendron giganteum</ce:italic>, grows in mid-elevation (1400–2000 m) forests with mild winters and moderate summer temperatures (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0080" refid="bib65">Sillett et al., 2019b</ce:cross-ref>), whereas <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> occupies coastal forests &lt; 1000 m elevation distributed along a north-south latitudinal gradient of decreasing precipitation and increasing temperatures (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0085" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). By virtue of extreme fire and decay resistance, <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> rainforests hold the global maximum aboveground biomass (&gt; 4000 Mg ha<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup>), including prodigious quantities of deadwood available for tree-ring sampling (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0010" refid="bib87 bib66">Van Pelt et al., 2016; Sillett et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Annually dated (hereafter, crossdated) tree-ring chronologies promote a variety of scientific inquiries, including investigations of climate, ecology, fire, seismology, and archeology (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0090" refid="bib76">St. George, 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0095" refid="bib49">Pearl et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Reference chronologies are fundamentally valuable as baselines for dating other tree-ring records, often filling spatial and temporal gaps and associated with larger studies (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0100" refid="bib4">Biondi, 1992</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0105" refid="bib9">Brown et al., 1992</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0110" refid="bib58">Roibu et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Crossdating is based on the common pattern of inter-annual variation among a population of trees, and replication reveals shared climatic and environmental signals (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0115" refid="bib25">Fritts, 1976</ce:cross-ref>). The quality and useful length of a chronology can be described by its signal strength, a statistic based on sample depth and synchrony (i.e., common variance) of constituent series (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0120" refid="bib23">Esper and Gärtner, 2001</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0125" refid="bib76">St. George, 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Expressed population signal (EPS), a commonly used measure of signal strength that depends on sample depth and rbar (mean between-tree correlation), generally declines back in time with reduced replication (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0130" refid="bib91">Wigley et al., 1984</ce:cross-ref>). Networks of ring indices enable spatially-explicit investigations of environmental variables such as climatic sensitivities (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0015" refid="bib6 bib24 bib85">Briffa, 2000; Frank and Esper, 2005; Touchan et al., 2014</ce:cross-refs>), and groupings based on shared signals across the landscape guide creation of robust regional chronologies (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0135" refid="bib37">Larson et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Such chronologies are currently lacking for many tree species, including <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">While the long-term potential and scientific value of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronologies are clear, obstacles to crossdating are considerable. Identifying missing rings, or rings that are locally absent, is integral to crossdating and can provide environmental proxies (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0140" refid="bib48">Novak et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) but reach extreme levels for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> with discrepancies of &gt; 100 rings between heights on the trunk (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0145" refid="bib12">Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>) and radii on cross-sections (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0150" refid="bib26">Fritz, 1940</ce:cross-ref>). In primary forests, <ce:italic>S. sempervirens</ce:italic> of varying crown classes averages 3.1% missing rings (maximum = 12.5%), much greater than <ce:italic>S. giganteum</ce:italic>, which averages 0.1% (maximum = 0.9%; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0155" refid="bib12">Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). In comparison, among Northern Hemisphere species on the International Tree-Ring Data Bank (ITRDB), <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> has the most missing rings, averaging 0.8% of all rings absent (maximum = ∼ 8.5% absent for an individual tree-ring record; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0160" refid="bib77">St. George et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>). Missing rings occur when growth is not initiated on part of the cambium, can be caused by a range of environmental stressors (e.g., climate, disturbances), and may vary by latitude, elevation, and canopy position (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0020" refid="bib88 bib40">Villalba et al., 1997; Lorimer et al., 1999</ce:cross-refs>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0165" refid="bib77">St. George et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0170" refid="bib48">Novak et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>). Missing rings are more common during periods of low growth rate for <ce:italic>Acer saccharum</ce:italic> among both canopy and understory trees (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0175" refid="bib40">Lorimer et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>), and frequency increases with ring age and decreases with height for <ce:italic>Pinus halepensis</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0025" refid="bib47 bib48">Novak et al., 2011, 2016</ce:cross-refs>). Cross-sections of 22 <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in secondary forests reveal missing rings in all trees with the probability of obtaining maximum ring count increasing with height above ground (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0180" refid="bib90">Waring and O’Hara, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). Ring wedging (i.e., pinching, discontinuous rings, lack of circuit uniformity) is a confounding feature for dating <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> associated with missing rings and may be unrelated to climate (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0030" refid="bib27 bib26 bib12 bib89">Fritz and Averill, 1924; Fritz, 1940; Carroll et al., 2014; Voelker et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>). Crossdating in a related species (<ce:italic>Juniperus communis</ce:italic>) with ring wedging is successful in only half the samples even among a subset of less-problematic radii (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0185" refid="bib50">Pellizzari et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Lower trunks of large <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> have buttresses extending &gt; 10 m above ground and basal complexities such as burn cavities, burls, and sprouting (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0190" refid="bib87">Van Pelt et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) that may affect crossdating success. Suppressed trees and trees with spiral compression wood also diminish efficacy of dating <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>, as evidenced by fewer rings annually resolved for trees in primary forests with these traits compared to those without (67 vs. 88% and 60 vs. 88%, respectively; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0195" refid="bib12">Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">Despite these obstacles, multi-centennial crossdating of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> has been achieved. A 272-year fire history (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0200" refid="bib8">Brown and Swetnam, 1994</ce:cross-ref>) and millennium-length isotope chronology (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0205" refid="bib89">Voelker et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) both relied primarily on portions of deadwood. Whole-trunk dendrochronology for large, standing trees is a relatively new approach that moves beyond traditional ground-based methods or stem analysis of cross-sections and builds on an early suggestion to focus on upper radii of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> for crossdating improvement (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0210" refid="bib61">Schulman, 1940</ce:cross-ref>). Our sampling strategy of climbing <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> with free-hanging ropes to acquire replicate increment cores at regular height intervals along the main trunk facilitated multi-centennial to millennium-length crossdating at nine primary forests (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0035" refid="bib12 bib15">Carroll et al., 2014, 2018a</ce:cross-refs>) that were utilized for study of aboveground tree and forest attributes (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0040" refid="bib72 bib67 bib69 bib66 bib70">Sillett et al., 2010, 2015b, 2019a, 2020, 2021</ce:cross-refs>), dendroclimatic relationships (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0045" refid="bib12 bib15">Carroll et al., 2014, 2018a</ce:cross-refs>), and tree-ring indicators of fire (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0215" refid="bib15">Carroll et al., 2018a</ce:cross-ref>b). More recently, <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>’s response to environmental change was evaluated in 45 primary and mature secondary forests distributed across the species range revealing increased drought sensitivity from north to south (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0220" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) that should be conducive to regional classification.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Here we generate reference chronologies for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> at 47 widely distributed locations, expanding and updating the dendrochronological network for this species. We examine coherence between individual location chronologies to establish robust regional chronologies. Given the challenges deciphering the <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> tree-ring record, we investigate constraints on crossdating to provide insights for future study and intensively examine ten old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> to illustrate concepts. We have five specific questions: (1) What is the signal strength of crossdated <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronologies across its native range? (2) Based on shared variation, how can location chronologies be combined into robust regional and subregional chronologies? (3) To what degree is crossdating success related to variation in tree size and age, landscape position, and growth increment? (4) Where is crossdating success maximized along the trunk height gradient? (5) How does whole-trunk sampling overcome obstacles and present opportunities for dendrochronological analysis of old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>? Organization of this study, which attempts to answer these questions via several analyses, is summarized in <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0005"/>
                     <ce:cross-ref id="cr0225" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0010" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0030">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0035">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">Study locations in 32 primary forests, 13 mature secondary forests (logged once), and two other locations based primarily on deadwood spanned gradients of latitude, elevation, distance from ocean, and climatic conditions encompassing the <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> range (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0230" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:bold>,</ce:bold> 
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0010"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0235" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>). Location numbers, descriptions, and trees match those in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0240" refid="bib71">Sillett et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref>, although tree selection varied slightly for locations <ce:bold>5</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>11</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>13</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>20</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>24</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>31</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>34</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>38</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>44</ce:bold> with additional intermediate and subordinate trees utilized here. We added two nearby locations (<ce:bold>15 A</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>34 A</ce:bold>) with living trees and deadwood sampled. Descriptions of study locations are found in <ce:bold>Appendix A</ce:bold>.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0040">Tree selection and sampling</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">A total of 278 trees at 47 locations were sampled from 2005 to 2021 with 5952 series primarily from increment cores. Living trees were in either primary (199 trees) or secondary (70 trees) forests, including five veterans that survived late 19th to early 20th century logging and two trees that regenerated after partial logging in primary forests. Trees ranged from 41 to 116 m tall, 86–750 cm <ce:italic>f</ce:italic>DBH (functional diameter at breast height), and 96 ± 4–2342 ± 16 yr old (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0245" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Nine dead trees had samples cut with a chainsaw as full (one at <ce:bold>l1</ce:bold>, two at <ce:bold>34 A</ce:bold>) or partial (three at <ce:bold>44</ce:bold>) cross-sections from downed trunks or plunge cuts from stumps (three at <ce:bold>15 A</ce:bold>). Subsets of trees were utilized for various analyses (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0250" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">Living trees were climbed with free-hanging ropes, and replicate increment cores (5 mm diameter) were collected at ≤ 10-m height intervals along the main trunk. Shorter cores aiming for just beyond the sapwood boundary were collected at or near breast height (BH, 1.37 m) and top of buttress (TB, 1.9–14.3 m) to limit the possibility of water leakage by deep coring at these lower positions. Holes were plugged with bark after core extraction. Most trees were similarly sampled with cores targeted as close to pith as possible from 10 m to treetop using borers up to 99 cm long. For trees with broken tops, sampling continued on the dominant reiterated trunk. Two cores were collected per height unless trunk diameter was &gt; 2 or 3 m, then 3–4 cores were collected, respectively. Coring locations were spaced around the trunk circumference, avoiding irregularities (e.g., burls, branch collars).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">
                        <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> at 37 locations measured from 2017 to 2021 had four to eight (usually five) dominant or co-dominant trees sampled within 1 km of each other (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0255" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>). Of these locations, trees at <ce:bold>4</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>8</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>15</ce:bold>, and <ce:bold>21</ce:bold> were part of a manipulative experiment (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0260" refid="bib73">Sillett et al., 2018a</ce:cross-ref>) and trees at <ce:bold>28</ce:bold> were sampled previously (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0265" refid="bib15">Carroll et al., 2018a</ce:cross-ref>) with subsequent cores collected. <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> at <ce:bold>15 A</ce:bold> and <ce:bold>34 A</ce:bold> combined samples from deadwood with one standing tree (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0270" refid="bib14">Carroll et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Eight locations in primary forests (<ce:bold>5</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>11</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>13</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>20</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>24</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>34</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>38</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>44</ce:bold>) had trees from tagged populations in 1-ha plots (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0050" refid="bib12 bib13 bib67 bib66 bib87">Carroll et al., 2014, 2018b; Sillett et al., 2015b, 2020; Van Pelt et al., 2016</ce:cross-refs>). Trees at upland and lowland plots (<ce:bold>5</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>11</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>13)</ce:bold> were combined. Trees at these eight locations included dominant to subordinate individuals, and most trees were resampled after five years near the original coring positions for quantification of biomass increments (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0275" refid="bib66">Sillett et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>), providing rings to update previously published chronologies (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0280" refid="bib12">Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Deadwood near but outside plots at <ce:bold>11</ce:bold> (one tree) and <ce:bold>44</ce:bold> (three trees) was also sampled.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0045">Crossdating</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Increment cores were air dried, glued into wooden core mounts, and sanded with progressively finer grit to &gt; 600. Care was taken to sand edges of cores showing tight or wedged rings to discern ring boundaries. Deadwood was similarly dried and sanded. Samples were inspected under a stereo microscope, marked with pencil, scanned at 1200 dpi, and measured to 0.001 mm using WinDendro (v.2009b, Régent Instruments Inc., Québec, Canada). Samples were viewed under the microscope in parallel to setting ring boundaries for measurements with particular focus on areas of narrow or wedged rings that were noted as likely positions for missing rings. Crossdating was achieved by listing visual marker years (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0285" refid="bib93">Yamaguchi, 1991</ce:cross-ref>) and staggered correlation analysis on overlapping segments via COFECHA (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0290" refid="bib30">Holmes, 1983</ce:cross-ref>). Marker, or pointer, years were identified when a year was consistently small, large, or had thick latewood, and sequences of markers were used as unique signatures for dating. If initial visual crossdating was not possible, COFECHA was used to generate options for number of missing rings based on correlations, and dating was always confirmed by pattern matching under the microscope. Crossdating was completed for series per tree, then tree-level crossdating was compared within locations. Chronologies from nearby locations corroborated dating for earliest years. Trees at <ce:bold>20</ce:bold> were used to place several missing rings for the oldest tree at <ce:bold>24</ce:bold> (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0295" refid="bib12">Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). We used a chronology from Humboldt Redwoods State Park (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0300" refid="bib89">Voelker et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>) to date an inner floating section of the oldest tree at <ce:bold>18</ce:bold>. Northern chronologies were used to crossdate stumps and a veteran tree at <ce:bold>15 A</ce:bold>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Due to the complex nature of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>, a system of coding rings for crossdating confidence was utilized (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0010"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0305" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>). High crossdating confidence occurred when annual resolution or absolute dating was achieved. Moderate crossdating confidence occurred when a small number of missing ring(s) was placed in the most likely position, but feasible alternatives existed (e.g., missing ring 1739 or 1742) or when multiple missing rings were in an area of tight growth (e.g., three missing rings among 10 small rings). Moderate classification recognized sections with some ambiguity or lack of a clear match (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0310" refid="bib40">Lorimer et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>). Rings with no annual resolution were placed in two categories, bound or not bound. Bound occurred when total number of years in a section of known length was determined and that section was bracketed by dated rings (e.g., 20 missing rings spanning a century with absolute dating before and after). Not bound occurred when crossdating stopped before the innermost ring, precluding placement of missing rings. All intact rings were measured and categorized, and sections of decayed or missing pieces were noted (and measured if possible).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0050">Tree size, growth, and age</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">Measurements and calculations made to quantify size, growth, and age of study trees are reported elsewhere (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0315" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) and briefly summarized here. Allometric equations and field measurements permitted calculations of aboveground attributes, including biomass, leaf mass, and wood volume (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0055" refid="bib66 bib71">Sillett et al., 2020, 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Annual increments of main trunk growth were reconstructed as far back as crossdating allowed based on series dated with high and moderate confidence. We used conic equations to compute main trunk wood volume and cambium area at annual increments. We computed specific volume increment (SVI), or the trunk-averaged radial increment (mm yr<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup>), as wood volume increment (WVI) divided by average cambium area during that year. Biomass increment was predicted from WVI (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0060" refid="bib69 bib66">Sillett et al., 2019a, 2020</ce:cross-refs>). Tree age was estimated as the <ce:italic>y</ce:italic>-intercept of the linear relationship between trunk age and height at 10-m intervals up to 60 m unless curvilinearity was present, in which case trunk age estimates at 50 or 60 m were excluded from regressions. When increment cores did not reach pith, trunk age was determined by estimating remaining years to pith via height- and location-specific equations predicting ring width as a power function of wood radius (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0320" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>, see Table S2).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0035" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0055">Location chronologies</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">Chronologies were individually generated for all 278 trees and then combined into 47 location chronologies. First, for each tree we selected series with high crossdating confidence and series length ≥ 30 yr. Last year was truncated if sampled before November to ensure complete growth rings. A cubic smoothing spline with a 50% frequency cutoff at 32 yr (32-yr spline) was applied to each series via ARSTAN (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0325" refid="bib16">Cook, 1985</ce:cross-ref>) to remove the geometric growth trend and low-frequency variation. This isolated higher frequency year-to-year variability suitable for crossdating (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0330" refid="bib28">Grissino-Mayer, 2001</ce:cross-ref>). Ring widths were standardized around an index of 1.0. The standard version (STD) of each tree chronology (mean = 21 series) was combined to generate a location chronology with no further detrending in ARSTAN. A biweight robust mean was used for chronologies to reduce the influence of outliers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0335" refid="bib17">Cook and Kairiukstis, 1990</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.6</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0060">Regional associations and chronologies</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">Regional assessments utilized correlations among location chronologies and principal components analysis (PCA) to guide chronology building. We used chronologies in 32 primary forests with ≥ four living trees. Pearson correlation coefficients were computed for all pairs of STD chronologies (1701–present). PCA provided a dimensionality-reduction method, helpful for interpretation of similarity among inter-related chronologies. Orthogonal PCs maintained as much variability as possible, and the loading or score per chronology represented its relationship to that PC. PCA employed a correlation cross-product matrix (1740–2013) via PC-ORD (version 7.8). Once groupings were identified, regional chronologies combined STD tree chronologies from primary forests in that region as previously described. Regional chronologies were truncated to maintain ≥ two-tree replication, but the northern chronology was truncated at three trees due to low correlations for early years between two trees at <ce:bold>13</ce:bold> and <ce:bold>18</ce:bold> (<ce:italic>r</ce:italic> = 0.18 for 668–988; <ce:italic>r</ce:italic> ≤ 0.22 for 8 of 13 overlapping 50-yr segments).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0045" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.7</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0065">Chronology statistics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Chronology statistics, including mean correlation among pairs of series (rbar) and running expressed population signal (EPS), were calculated via dplR library in R (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0340" refid="bib10">Bunn, 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0345" refid="bib55">R Core Team, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). EPS for 50-yr windows lagged by 25 yr assessed changing signal strength over time. Recognizing the relatively low replication per location due to intensive within-tree sampling and the goal of generating crossdated chronologies rather than climatic reconstructions, we flagged location chronologies with EPS &lt; 0.75 and used the common 0.85 threshold (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0065" refid="bib91 bib5">Wigley et al., 1984; Briffa, 1995</ce:cross-refs>) to assess regional chronologies with higher tree replication.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0050" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.8</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0070">Tree-level crossdating metrics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">We calculated crossdating metrics, including percent rings per category as well as missing rings, and comparative analyses were limited to similarly-sampled trees (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0070" refid="tbl0005 tbl0010">Tables 1 and 2</ce:cross-refs>). As a proxy for crossdating challenges, we generally used the category of undated rings bound by dated rings because inner rings of older trees were often not dated due to low replication. Wilcoxon rank sum tests assessed differences in metrics between trees in primary and secondary forests.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">Nonparametric multiplicative regression (NPMR) assessed the influence of landscape position and tree attributes on crossdating efficacy for 122 trees in primary forests. Trees in secondary forests were excluded due to relative lack of undated and missing rings. Predictors included latitude, elevation, distance from ocean, tree age, tree height, <ce:italic>f</ce:italic>DBH, DTB, crown volume, aboveground biomass, leaf mass, and heartwood volume. Response variables were percent undated (but bound) and missing rings. NPMR accounts for interactions among predictors, combines predictors multiplicatively rather than additively, and requires no assumptions about response surface shape (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0075" refid="bib43 bib44">McCune, 2006, 2011</ce:cross-refs>). Models used a local multiplicative kernel smoothing function and leave-one-out cross validation to estimate response variables. Local linear quantitative model form was deployed in forward stepwise regressions of individual responses against all sets of predictors. Minimum data-to-predictor ratio was set to 40. Minimum average neighborhood size was 10% of sample size. Model fit was expressed as cross-validated correlation—x<ce:italic>R</ce:italic>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>—differing from traditional <ce:italic>R</ce:italic>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> in that each datum was excluded from the basis for estimating the response at that point (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0350" refid="bib45">McCune and Mefford, 2009</ce:cross-ref>). Predictors were ignored unless they contributed ≥ 5% of model x<ce:italic>R</ce:italic>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>. NPMR was conducted via HyperNiche (v2.30, MjM Software Design).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">To understand how crossdating efficacy aligned with growth increment, we calculated frequency of undated rings by units of SVI, focusing on the most challenging trees (&gt; 3.5% rings undated but bound). For each tree, we calculated percent undated but bound rings per year and used only years with ≥ 5 series overlapping with SVI metrics. Percent undated rings was averaged in bins defined by SVI from 0 to 2.5 mm yr<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup> in 0.5 mm yr<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup> categories. To test for differences among categories, we used Friedman’s nonparametric rank sum test with unreplicated, complete block design (tree as blocking variable), SVI category as group, and percent undated rings as dependent variable. Differences between categories were assessed with exact post hoc tests for all pairwise comparisons of Friedman rank sums (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0355" refid="bib22">Eisinga et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>) with <ce:italic>P</ce:italic>-value adjustment for multiple comparisons to control for false discovery rate (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0360" refid="bib3">Benjamini and Hochberg, 1995</ce:cross-ref>). Tests were run in R using stats and PMCMRplus packages (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0365" refid="bib54">Pohlert, 2022</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0370" refid="bib55">R Core Team, 2022</ce:cross-ref>). We calculated Kendall rank correlation coefficients (τ) for comparisons between times series of SVI and percent undated rings for the 28 trees using Real Statistics Resource Pack (real-statistics.com) for Excel (v16.56, Microsoft Inc.).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Whole-trunk sampling provided access to rings of different wood radii and cambial ages (i.e., number years from pith at given height), permitting assessment of crossdating efficacy along gradients of size and age. We analyzed the same 28 trees and calculated mean wood radius, cambial age, and ring width for two categories: undated (but bound) and dated (high confidence) rings. Each year sampled had a measured ring width and associated crossdating category, and for each year we calculated wood radius and cambial age as far back as possible. The Wilcoxon rank sum test assessed differences between categories per metric.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0055" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.9</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0075">Crossdating metrics by height within tree</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">To evaluate the effect of sample height on crossdating, we compared percent undated rings, percent missing rings, interseries correlation, and mean ring width at BH, 10 m, and 10-m height intervals for trees in primary forests. A common period was set per tree to control for external influences (e.g., climate, disturbances) over time, and the period varied among trees to accommodate differences in core lengths and crossdating categories. We selected two common periods, a shorter one maximizing the number of heights, including shallow cores at BH and upper heights to 70 m, and a longer one maximizing number of years analyzed, including only deeper cores at 10–50 m. Analysis focused on differences between heights on the main trunk, excluding reiterated trunks that were much younger. Unless sampled at 10 m, cores at TB were not considered. Both bound and unbound categories were used to calculate undated rings to include shorter cores where undated inner rings were not attributable to low replication. Undated sections were included in missing ring analysis only if bound by dated years (so total number missing rings was known) and the entire section was in the common period. Interseries correlation was calculated by COFECHA as Pearson’s coefficient between a series and the master chronology (i.e., series ≥ 30 yr dated with high confidence) using the 32-yr spline default (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0375" refid="bib30">Holmes, 1983</ce:cross-ref>). To maintain equivalent contribution to the master chronology, we used the same number of series per height (2 or 3) per tree. We employed Friedman’s nonparametric rank sum tests in an unreplicated, complete block design (tree as blocking variable, height as group, crossdating metrics as dependent variables) to determine if metrics differed among heights. We used post hoc exact tests for all pairwise comparisons as previously described.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0060" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.10</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0080">Case studies of ten trees &gt; 1000 yr old</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">For ten <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> &gt; 1000 yr old, we generated time series of crossdating using all series to tally confidence categories for all years. Within-tree replication averaged 30 series (range 22–45). Time series of biomass increments were calculated per tree as previously described (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0380" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Scale models of tree structure were generated via field measurements of trunks, segmented appendages (reiterated trunks, limbs), and crown size (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0385" refid="bib35">Kramer et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). When possible, we dated top breaks by aging reiterated trunks just above the break. Age difference between the reiterated top and main trunk just below the break determined age of the broken piece. Size of the piece was deduced from wood radius at break height during event year and did not include bark.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0065" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0085">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">Width was measured and crossdating categorized for 1286,405 rings from 278 trees and 5952 series. Of these rings, 82.9% dated with high confidence, 3.6% dated with moderate confidence, 8.3% were undated but bound by dated rings, 4.9% were undated and not bound, 0.3% were decayed or lost during collection, and 3.2% were identified as missing rings (excluding rings in prior two categories). Subsets of data correspond with various analyses (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0390" refid="tbl0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>). Raw measurements of crossdated ring widths are provided in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0395" refid="sec0135">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="sec0070" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0090">Location chronologies</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">Series dated with high confidence supported ring-width chronologies for 47 locations across the geographic distribution of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> from 86 to 1687 yr in length (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0400" refid="tbl0010">Tables 2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0405" refid="sec0135">S2</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0015"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0410" refid="fig0015">Figs. 3</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0415" refid="sec0135">S1</ce:cross-ref>). Correlations (rbar) among pairs of trees per location averaged 0.51 ± 0.01 ( ± 1 SE) with no difference between primary and secondary forests (<ce:italic>t</ce:italic>
                        <ce:inf loc="post">23</ce:inf> = 1.3, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> = 0.20). Missing rings among series used for chronologies averaged 0.5% (range 0.0–1.9). Chronologies averaged six trees (range 3–23) and 126 series (range 19–367) with replication declining back in time. Differences between sampled and included series corresponded to undated rings (e.g., 1400 s, location <ce:bold>9</ce:bold>) or series length &lt; 30 yr, apparent for recent decades due to upper radii from younger trees (e.g., location <ce:bold>4</ce:bold>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0420" refid="sec0135">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>). Six millennial-length chronologies traversed the distribution, 29 chronologies spanned ≥ 500 yr, and veteran trees covered 200–274 yr. Many chronologies exhibited robust statistics for centuries (e.g., 14 with continually robust signal and ≥ 2-tree replication for &gt; 400 yr and two for &gt; 800 yr), although portions up to centuries in length were limited to one-tree or EPS &lt; 0.75, and some sections included only one series (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0425" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0075" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0095">Regional associations and chronologies</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">Relationships among <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> indices at 32 locations in primary forests distinguished shared signals in the northern (&gt; 40°) compared to southern (south of the San Francisco Peninsula, &lt; 37.5°) region. Shared variance between ring indices averaged 24.6 ± 1.0% ( ± 1 SE; range 7.6–56.4) in the north, 21.1 ± 1.6% (range 6.2–46.8) in the south, and 2.9 ± 0.25% (range 0.0–13.4) between north and south (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0020"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0430" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a top). Strength of shared variance among locations across the distribution decayed with distance between 496 pairs and expressed a negative exponential relationship (<ce:italic>R</ce:italic>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> = 0.66; y = 0.3623 <ce:italic>e</ce:italic>
                        <ce:sup loc="post">-0.0068x</ce:sup>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0435" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>a bottom). Regional correlations among chronologies were supported by PCA loadings, where the first two PCs accounted for 81.7% of total variation, and regional and sub-regional clusters were spatially distinct (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0440" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>b). Statistical groupings led to creation of two regional and four sub-regional chronologies for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0445" refid="sec0135">Table S3</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0450" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>c). The 1032-yr northern chronology spanned years 988–2019 (108 trees) with sub-regional chronologies for 41–42° (988–2019, 70 trees) and 40–41° (1226–2019, 38 trees). The 865-yr southern <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronology spanned years 1156–2020 (52 trees) with sub-regions for the Santa Cruz Mountains (1312–2019, 31 trees) and the Santa Lucia Mountains (1297–2020, 21 trees). While locations <ce:bold>22</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>28</ce:bold>, <ce:bold>31</ce:bold>, and <ce:bold>33</ce:bold> grouped among northern or southern regions in PCA, they were excluded due to geographical separation. EPS levels ≥ 0.85 indicated the most statistically reliable chronology portions and extended to 1070 and 1471 in the north and south, respectively. Marker years differed between regions. The strongest low-growth years (≤ 2.5 standard deviations, 1500–2019) in chronological order were 1596, 1729, 1739, 1741, 1850, 1959 in the north and 1500, 1579, 1580, 1777, 1841, 1844, 1864, 1865 in the south.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0080" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0100">Tree-level crossdating metrics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">The 278 trees averaged 92.2% of rings annually resolved (89.8% high and 2.4% moderate confidence), 7.6% of rings not annually resolved (3.9% bound by dated rings, 3.7% not bound as inner sections), and 1.7% of rings locally absent (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0015"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0455" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>). Missing rings reached a maximum of 11.8% for a 44.8 m tall, 387 ± 80 yr old, subordinate tree at location <ce:bold>44</ce:bold>. Trees from mixed crown classes in primary forests averaged 15.3% undated and 3.1% missing rings with crossdating comparisons between crown classes for most of these trees described in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0460" refid="bib12">Carroll et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref>. Trees in primary forests had more missing rings (mean ± 95% confidence interval, Wilcoxon test statistics: 1.6 ± 0.4 vs. 0.0 ± 0.0%, <ce:italic>Z</ce:italic> = 9.2, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001), more undated rings (5.9 ± 1.0% vs. 0.3 ± 0.2, <ce:italic>Z</ce:italic> = 7.1, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001), and smaller ring widths (1.5 ± 0.1 mm vs. 4.1 ± 0.2, <ce:italic>Z</ce:italic> = 10.7, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001), respectively, than trees in secondary forests. Among these 122 dominant or co-dominant trees in primary forests, 15% had perfect dating and over half (57%) had ≥ 97% rings dated with high confidence.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">NPMR revealed effects of landscape position and tree attributes on crossdating metrics. Tree age and DTB predicted percent undated rings; and tree age, latitude, and heartwood volume predicted percent missing rings. The best models explained 40% and 57% of the variance for undated and missing rings, respectively, and age was the most important predictor in both (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0020"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0465" refid="tbl0020">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0025"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0470" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>). Percent undated rings increased nonlinearly with tree age and DTB with the latter response plateauing ∼ 200–300 cm. Percent missing rings increased nonlinearly with tree age and heartwood volume and exhibited multi-modal maxima for southern and northern latitudes. While age was the strongest predictor of undated and missing rings, an increasing range of variability occurred among the oldest trees. The interquartile range of undated rings was 0.0–0.0 for trees ≤ 500 yr, 0.0–5.3% for trees 501–1000 yr, and 6.3–25.0% for trees &gt; 1000 yr old, and for missing rings was 0.0–0.6%, 0.4–2.7%, and 2.2–9.2% by age class, respectively.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">Percent undated rings for 28 <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> with the most challenging crossdating increased with lower trunk radial increments (SVI; Friedman rank sum test: χ<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> = 85.7, df = 4, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001; <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0030"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0475" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>). Kendall’s rank coefficients (τ) showed a negative relationship between SVI and percent undated rings for 27 of 28 trees (<ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001) with a mean τ of 0.45. Comparisons of mean ring width, wood radius, and cambial age of dated and undated rings for the same trees showed only ring width exhibiting a difference between categories (mean ± 95% confidence interval, Wilcoxon test statistics: 1.1 ± 0.1 vs. 0.4 ± 0.1 mm, <ce:italic>Z</ce:italic> = 6.3, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001). Wood radius (0.6 ± 0.1 vs. 0.6 ± 0.1, <ce:italic>Z = 1.2</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> = 0.23) and cambial age (403 ± 65 vs. 500 ± 76 yr, <ce:italic>Z</ce:italic> = 1.9, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> = 0.06) did not differ significantly between dated and undated rings.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0085" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0105">Crossdating metrics by height within tree</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">Height above ground affected percent undated rings, percent missing rings, interseries correlation, and ring width (<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl0025"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0480" refid="tbl0025">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>). Pairwise comparisons indicated differences between height categories using complementary analyses of 1.4–70 m and 10–50 m (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0035"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0485" refid="fig0035">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>). Undated rings ranked higher at lower positions, exemplified by 10 m compared to upper heights (46 trees) and BH compared to 40 and 60 m (27 trees). Missing rings generally ranked higher with lower position except BH, which did not differ from heights 10–70 m. Interseries correlation ranked lower and ring width ranked higher at BH compared to all upper heights to 70 m (58 trees).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0090" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0110">Case studies of ten trees &gt; 1000 yr old</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">Tree models illustrated size, structure, and individuality of ten <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> &gt; 1000 yr old used as case studies of whole-trunk dendrochronology (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0040"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0490" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>a). Crossdating classification showed the complexity of resolving rings of old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>, synchrony between undated years and reduced productivity, and how whole-trunk sampling enabled growth reconstructions despite imperfect dating (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0495" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>b). Tree-level variability was illustrated by the contrast between trees with near complete dating (e.g., trees 61 and 42: &lt; 0.25% undated, &lt; 0.05% missing rings) and trees with most rings unresolved (e.g., trees 86 and 35: ≥ 51% undated, ≥ 9% missing rings). Trees often had discrete sections where crossdating dropped during growth reduction but was bound by dated rings. For tree 100, dating fell from near perfect to 16.7%, and cores had up to 53% missing rings in the 15th century, aligning with reduced growth (mean 200 vs. 66 kg yr<ce:sup loc="post">-1</ce:sup>, 14th vs. 15th century, respectively). Nevertheless, growth increments were computed because wood radii and number of years during undated sections were known, and increments were interpolated from dated series. Sections with no cores dated precluded inter-annual reconstruction of biomass, exemplified by a 682-yr gap for tree 86 with hundreds of missing rings (e.g., maximum 391 on 1332-yr core from 10 m). Interrupted crossdating generally resumed for innermost (generally larger) rings. However, crossdating ceased in year 988 although ring counts reached year 361 for tree 111.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">Whole-trunk sampling enabled event dating and assessment of biomass dynamics related to disturbances. Synchronous patterns for trees 121 and 123 (location <ce:bold>2</ce:bold>) showed reduced biomass increment (and crossdating efficacy) in the 17th century followed by growth release (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0500" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>b). Tree-ring indicators suggested a fire in 1699–1700 evidenced by traumatic resin ducts, post-event micro rings, and subsequent growth releases in two nearby individuals. Trees 42 and 151 had upswings of biomass increment reflective of a regional 20th century growth surge, and tree 50 showed a multi-location mid-20th century growth reduction detailed in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0505" refid="bib71">Sillett et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref>. Trunk breakage and reiteration indicated prior injury, and within-tree sampling enabled dating of such events for two trees (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0510" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>ab). Tree 42’s main trunk broke at 62.8 m, and age of the reiteration immediately above the break dated this event to 1620. Loss of the 114-yr-old, 36-cm-diameter piece corresponded with a 22% drop in biomass increment (10- and 50-yr windows). The main trunk of tree 35 broke at 79.5 m with multiple reiterations. Age of the dominant reiterated trunk at 80.6 m was 532 yr. Allowing a lag for the reiteration to gain 90 cm in height, the snap was dated to 1467, coincident with a step-change in biomass increment (25% reduction for 10- and 50-yr windows). The age of the main trunk 2.1 m below the break constrained the broken piece to &lt; 300 yr old and &lt; 65 cm diameter.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0095" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0115">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">Annually-resolved tree rings advance many fields of inquiry, and we demonstrate that <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> can be crossdated despite obstacles such as discontinuous rings and access to upper trunks of tall trees. Successful dating of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> contributes to a growing list of species available for dendrochronological research from iterative work on <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0515" refid="bib62">Schulman, 1958</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0520" refid="bib60">Salzer et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>) to recent advances dating low- and high-latitude species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0525" refid="bib49">Pearl et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Dominant or co-dominant <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in mature secondary forests date at near complete levels as they regenerate in high light environments, permitting reconstruction of growth histories valuable for establishing realistic management targets (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0080" refid="bib70 bib71">Sillett et al., 2021, 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Discussion focuses on primary forests to refine approaches for successful dendrochronology of old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="sec0100" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0120">Location and regional chronologies</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">While the western United States is duly represented on the ITRDB, the network of 47 <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronologies populates the Central and North Coast Bioregions, which, like many coastal tree-ring records, are underrepresented (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0530" refid="bib86">Tucker and Pearl, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Long <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronologies (30 &gt; 500 yr, 6 &gt; 1000 yr) are noteworthy given that most of the &gt; 3000 chronologies on the ITRDB extend up to 300 yr with ∼ 400 predating 1400 and only ∼ 120 spanning over a millennium (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0535" refid="bib76">St. George, 2014</ce:cross-ref>). High within-tree replication yields relatively low tree replication compared to standard ground-based sampling, contributing to sections where signal strength drops to a less reliable level, though target replication depends on research questions and cannot be generally prescribed (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0085" refid="bib63 bib23">Schweingruber et al., 1992; Esper and Gärtner, 2001</ce:cross-refs>). Chronology statistics must be considered before application (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0540" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>). The rangewide network provides baselines for newly gathered or previously undated material, expediting an array of inquiries. For example, while crossdating has not limited fire histories for most conifers, the spatial distribution of the fire-scar network in North America is near void for the <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> range (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0545" refid="bib42">Margolis et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) despite <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> being one of the most fire-frequent conifers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0550" refid="bib81">Stevens et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Point-specific references can guide dating of fire-scarred sections from stumps as well as increment cores from living trees via fire indicators (e.g., post-fire low growth asynchronous with drought, anatomical markers; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0555" refid="bib8">Brown and Swetnam, 1994</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-refs id="crs0090" refid="bib15 bib13">Carroll et al., 2018a, b</ce:cross-refs>) as exemplified by a fire detected in 1829 at location <ce:bold>43</ce:bold>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">Although deadwood represents a small portion of study trees (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0560" refid="tbl0015">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>), we demonstrate its utility as a source of viable records with likelihood of dating enhanced by reference chronologies. Deadwood underpins much chronology building (e.g., <ce:cross-ref id="cr0565" refid="bib9">Brown et al., 1992</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-refs id="crs0095" refid="bib78 bib79">Stahle et al., 2012, 2013</ce:cross-refs>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0570" refid="bib58">Roibu et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) and is particularly useful for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> given its decay-resistant heartwood and scarcity of primary forests. Despite loss of sapwood, intact heartwood from stumps contributes to a 745-yr chronology (with gaps, <ce:bold>15 A</ce:bold>) near Humboldt Bay, where very little primary forest remains. Opportunistic sampling of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> can unlock information stored in freshly-fallen deadwood with dating assisted by known last year. We utilize a 708-yr cross-section from a recently-fallen tree to enhance early replication for chronology <ce:bold>11</ce:bold>. This section also includes resin ducts, discolored wood, and ring separation dating to 1714, coincident with fire scars on other trees in the region (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0575" refid="bib8">Brown and Swetnam, 1994</ce:cross-ref>). As old trees topple in saturated soils during high-wind events, samples may be obtained as trunks are cleared from roads and trails. Such records may be particularly useful for isotopic analyses that require substantial material (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0580" refid="bib89">Voelker et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">Associations between <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> location chronologies define regions sharing climatic signals. The southern group, composed of drought-sensitive trees (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0585" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>), is especially relevant for forest management in the context of an increasingly arid climate (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0100" refid="bib21 bib52 bib84 bib94">Diffenbaugh et al., 2015; Pierce et al., 2018; Swain et al., 2018; Zhao et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>). Robust chronology statistics combined with high drought sensitivity of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in the Santa Lucia Mountains (mean <ce:italic>r</ce:italic> = 0.42 with summer standardized precipitation evapotranspiration index, SPEI, excluding hydrological refugium of location <ce:bold>43</ce:bold>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0590" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) demonstrate strong potential for hydroclimatic reconstructions. Regional chronologies may also be associated with ocean-atmosphere oscillations and related north-south precipitation patterns centered at a dipole transition zone of ∼ 40° (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0595" refid="bib56">Redmond and Koch, 1991</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0600" refid="bib83">Sung et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0605" refid="bib92">Wise, 2016</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> indices may be able to elucidate such dynamics, similar to observed precipitation anomalies between latitudinal groupings of another California species (<ce:italic>Quercus douglasii</ce:italic>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0610" refid="bib46">Meko et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0615" refid="bib79">Stahle et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>). Analyses of linkages with aspects of the California Current system may require detrending to capture lower-frequency (multi-annual to -decadal) variation to supplement higher-frequency (inter-annual) chronologies presented here (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0620" refid="bib20">Dettinger et al., 1998</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">The <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> chronologies establish a strong foundation for crossdating with temporally and spatially weaker sections defined to guide future improvements. For example, a spatially distinct signal may be refined for the central region, temporal gaps can be closed for indices near Humboldt Bay, and earliest years of chronologies can be verified, strengthened, and extended across the range. Future research accessing <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> tree-ring records will benefit from quantitative consideration of crossdating constraints.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0105" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0125">Tree-level crossdating metrics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">Tree age is the best predictor of crossdating efficacy (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0625" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>), and this relationship is strengthened by periods of reduced growth during millennial lifespans. Undated rings correspond with lower trunk-averaged radial increments (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0630" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>), and for these trees undated rings differ from dated rings in mean ring width but not in cambial age or wood radii. Crossdating success drops in synchrony with periods of lower biomass increment distributed across centuries for old trees (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0635" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>), and time series of biomass increment for 169 <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in primary forests show many episodes of reduced growth amid long-term trends (see Fig. S2 in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0640" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Disturbances that injure cambium, disrupt roots, or reduce photosynthetic capacity may cause growth reductions (e.g., geomorphic processes, fire, decapitation; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0645" refid="bib82">Stoffel and Bollschweiler, 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0650" refid="bib2">Bär et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> live in disturbance-prone environments as evidenced by canopy gap structural ensembles, downed logs, fire-scarred trunks, highly-reiterated trunks, and flood and mass movement deposits (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0105" refid="bib41 bib87">Lorimer et al., 2009; Van Pelt et al., 2016</ce:cross-refs>). Overtopped trees of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> and other species have more undated or missing rings (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0110" refid="bib40 bib12">Lorimer et al., 1999; Carroll et al., 2014</ce:cross-refs>), and while trees in this analysis are currently dominant or co-dominant, many spent prior centuries shaded by neighbors (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0655" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Primary <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> forests form a dynamic sylvatic mosaic, where disturbances such as fire and treefalls cause long-lived trees to adjust allocation of resources that affects crossdating efficacy (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0115" refid="bib75 bib87">Smith, 2008; Van Pelt et al., 2016</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">After accounting for tree age, the variables of DTB, latitude, and heartwood volume further explain crossdating efficacy and warrant interpretation. The influence of DTB on undated rings likely reflects the geometric consequence of decreasing radial increment with size. DTB is a particularly useful metric of trunk size as it is free of the influence of the basal buttress and integral to allometry of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> and other tall species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0120" refid="bib35 bib64 bib67 bib68 bib69 bib65 bib66">Kramer et al., 2018; Sillett et al., 2015a, b; 2018b, 2019a, b; 2020</ce:cross-refs>). The multi-modal effect of latitude on missing rings may be related to underlying environmental gradients. Missing rings are common in moisture-limited locations during drought years (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0660" refid="bib77">St. George et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref id="cr0665" refid="bib48">Novak et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>) and occur after some fires for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0125" refid="bib8 bib13">Brown and Swetnam, 1994; Carroll et al., 2018b</ce:cross-refs>). Both aridity and fire frequency increase from north to south (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0670" refid="bib80">Stephens et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Northern latitudes, on the other hand, have increased peak wind speeds conducive to winter storm damage (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0675" refid="bib41">Lorimer et al., 2009</ce:cross-ref>). High wind events cause growth reductions in conifers along the Oregon coast but also correspond with growth increases following canopy gap formation (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0680" refid="bib29">Hadley and Knapp, 2011</ce:cross-ref>). The influence of heartwood volume on missing rings may be related to tree size and resource allocation. Heartwood accumulates at an increasing rate as <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> enlarges with age, contributing to declining growth efficiency and increasing investment in decay resistance associated with longevity (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0685" refid="bib66">Sillett et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0110" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0130">Crossdating metrics by height within tree</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">Crossdating of the tallest species warrants consideration of sample height, and our findings provide guidance for sampling standing and downed trees. Crossdating metrics vary along the height gradient with series at BH having more undated rings than some upper heights despite having the largest ring widths (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0690" refid="fig0035">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>). Tree geometry explains the trend of increasing ring width with height due to younger cambial ages and smaller wood radii, and buttressing explains why this trend is disrupted with largest rings at BH. Basal buttressing is a morphological characteristic of many tree species, and models of ten old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> show its vertical extent (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0695" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>a). For trees in this analysis, top buttress height averages 5.8 ± 0.2 m, exceeding 10 m on two trees. Although interseries correlation may be influenced by distance between positions (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0700" refid="bib34">Kerhoulas and Kane, 2012</ce:cross-ref>), the reduced common signal at BH suggests buttressing and basal complexities decrease crossdating efficacy. Within-tree analysis of 24 eucalypts among four species show similar trends related to basal buttressing: ring width is largest on the lower trunk, greater than would be expected based on tree geometry, and within-tree correlation is lowest on the lower trunk, reflecting less circuit uniformity (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0705" refid="bib7">Brookhouse and Brack, 2008</ce:cross-ref>). Stem eccentricities in another buttressed conifer, <ce:italic>Tsuga heterophylla</ce:italic>, make lower portions of trunks non-round with off-centered piths and deeper fluting (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0710" refid="bib74">Singleton et al., 2003</ce:cross-ref>). Such dynamics highlight anomalies associated with buttressing as well as inherent limitations of BH-only sampling for quantifying whole-trunk growth in large trees (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0130" refid="bib34 bib31">Kerhoulas and Kane, 2012; Ishii et al., 2017</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">Percent missing rings exhibits a height-related trend, increasing with lower positions down to 10 m but not BH. This trend may be explained by tree geometry as well as xylogenesis involving interactions of intrinsic (e.g., hormones) and environmental (e.g., temperature) drivers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0715" refid="bib19">De Micco et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). Carbon allocation near the canopy may be prioritized during unfavorable conditions, as suggested by climate mediation of growth along the trunk for <ce:italic>F. sylvatica</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0720" refid="bib51">Peters et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Cores collected during the growing season show more complete ring formation with increasing sample height (personal observations), and within-tree sampling can help elucidate the dynamics of cambial phenology along the height gradient. As a general guide, sampling at the base of live crown (BLC, bottom of green ellipses, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0725" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>a) is recommended for successful crossdating of relatively long series without influence of trunk buttressing or branch collars. Mean BLC for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in the eight within-tree analyses (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0730" refid="fig0035">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>) ranged from 33 to 38 m above ground. In addition, sapwood cross-sectional area at BLC provides a robust predictor of whole-tree leaf area for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0735" refid="bib67">Sillett et al., 2015b</ce:cross-ref>). Supplementary sampling above and below BLC will balance considerations of particularly deep crowns, within-tree replication, and series length. We recommend sampling at least two cores per height due to within-height variation in ring widths and crossdating efficacy.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0115" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0135">Case studies of ten trees &gt; 1000 yr old</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">Whole-trunk sampling is integral to overcoming crossdating challenges particularly for old <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> and permits reconstruction of growth histories even when all series are not dated (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0740" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>b). This approach enhances study of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> but requires time and technical expertise. Crown models of ten old trees illustrate tree size and structural complexity (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0745" refid="fig0040">Fig. 8</ce:cross-ref>a), providing perspective on rope-based sampling. In the field and laboratory, the effort to measure and date one large <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> compares to that required for dozens of trees via traditional ground-based sampling. Such comprehensive work may be unnecessary for some goals as evidenced by near complete dating for trees in secondary forests and high success rates for over half the co-dominant or dominant trees in primary forests. For many older and larger trees, replicate coring along the trunk is indispensable for crossdating given the challenges of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> dendrochronology and the relationship between tree age and efficacy (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0750" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>). High within-tree replication allows complicated sections with tight and missing rings to be bridged for most trees but does not always succeed. Thus, we were able to reconstruct over 77 thousand years of growth history for 235 trees, including two (35, 111) with &gt; 1000 yr of continuous biomass increments (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0755" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Long, uninterrupted <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> tree-ring records may facilitate recovery of low-frequency environmental signals unencumbered by problems associated with shorter segment lengths (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0760" refid="bib18">Cook et al., 1995</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">Identifying disturbances in <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> forests and quantifying their impact on biomass dynamics is a powerful dendroecological application enhanced by whole-trunk sampling. Disturbances such as winter storms, fires, floods, and landslides induce growth reductions as trees recover from damage and releases as trees respond to higher resource availability (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0135" refid="bib8 bib82 bib29">Brown and Swetnam, 1994; Stoffel and Bollschweiler, 2008; Hadley and Knapp, 2011</ce:cross-refs>). Growth release detection techniques are becoming refined and increasingly used to investigate past disturbances (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0765" refid="bib1">Altman, 2020</ce:cross-ref>) with deterioration of resolution when disturbances are in quick succession (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0770" refid="bib59">Rubino and McCarthy, 2004</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> can play a particularly important role in dendroseismology, as some primary forests and stumps near the San Andreas Fault may be utilized for dating of prehistoric earthquakes, a goal long pursued (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0775" refid="bib32">Jacoby, 1994</ce:cross-ref>) but with renewed potential given advances demonstrated here. In addition to initiating changes in growth, seismic activity can damage trunks leading to reiterated tops (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0780" refid="bib33">Jacoby, 2010</ce:cross-ref>), as likely occurred for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> in Ft. Ross, California, after the 1906 earthquake (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0785" refid="bib38">Lawson, 1908</ce:cross-ref>). By sampling above and below trunk breaks, our methodology permits precise dating of disturbances and calculation of concurrent changes in biomass production. Resolution for event dating of top breaks can be further improved via targeted sampling.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0120" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0140">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">We present methods and insights for <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> that advance a century-long effort (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0790" refid="bib27">Fritz and Averill, 1924</ce:cross-ref>) to resolve and utilize annual rings of this long-lived species via within-trunk sampling of large trees. Location and regional chronologies provide complementary references that balance high within-tree replication necessary for crossdating success with the inherently lower tree replication corresponding with such effort. Regional expression of shared signals underscores growth variation in <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> forests with relevance for dendroclimatology and <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> conservation in an uncertain future (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0795" refid="bib71">Sillett et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Crossdating findings guide sampling for both standing and downed trees and point to novel applications such as dating crown-level disturbances. Strength of the whole-trunk sampling design is highlighted by our ability to crossdate <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> systematically and generate growth metrics supporting research on forest productivity and management for non-timber values. Future studies of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> can take advantage of this exhaustive effort by utilizing location and regional chronologies as references, considering regional associations in management, and developing the most appropriate sampling regime for quantifying tree growth responses to environmental change.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0125" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0145">Funding</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">This work was supported by <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs1" sponsor-id="http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100001328" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Save the Redwoods League</ce:grant-sponsor> (Redwoods and Climate Change Initiative, Phase 3) and <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Kenneth L. Fisher</ce:grant-sponsor> (Chair in Redwood Forest Ecology at Cal Poly Humboldt).</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0150">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0155">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">Marie Antoine, Jim Campbell-Spickler, and Russell Kramer assisted with fieldwork, including tree climbing and core sampling. We thank California State Parks, Redwood National Parks, Siskiyou National Forest, Six Rivers National Forest, Los Padres National Forest, City of Arcata, Bureau of Land Management, University of California, Land Trust of Napa County, Marin County Parks, East Bay Regional Park District, Santa Lucia Preserve, Santa Lucia Conservancy, the Save the Redwoods League, and other landowners for access to these forests. Russell Kramer helped to generate crown models in Fig. 8. We thank Bob Van Pelt and Marie Antoine for continued collaboration on the greater body of <ce:italic>Sequoia</ce:italic> research.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
               <ce:section id="sec0130" view="compact-standard">
                  <ce:label>Appendix A</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0160">Supporting information</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">Supplementary data associated with this article can be found in the online version at <ce:inter-ref id="ir0005" xlink:href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dendro.2023.126063" xlink:type="simple">doi:10.1016/j.dendro.2023.126063</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0135" view="extended">
                  <ce:label>Appendix A</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0165">Supplementary material</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:e-component id="ec0005">
                           <ce:caption id="cap0070">
                              <ce:simple-para id="sp0105" view="all">Supplementary material</ce:simple-para>
                           </ce:caption>
                           <ce:link id="lk0045" locator="mmc1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/46.1" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/mmc1"/>
                        </ce:e-component>
                     </ce:display>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:e-component id="ec0010">
                           <ce:label>Table S1</ce:label>
                           <ce:caption id="cap0075">
                              <ce:simple-para id="sp0110" view="all">Raw ring width measurements for <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> series crossdated with high confidence for 278 trees in 47 locations. Locations are organized from north to south and correspond with <ce:cross-ref id="cr0800" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                                 <ce:bold>,</ce:bold> 
                                 <ce:cross-ref id="cr0805" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>, and <ce:bold>Appendix A</ce:bold>. Series listed with location, tree, trunk ID, height (m) of sample on the trunk, and core. Trunk ID refers to main trunk (M) or reiterated trunks (e.g., M – 1, 1 – 2, etc.). Measurements are in microns and correspond with calendar years in the first column</ce:simple-para>
                           </ce:caption>
                           <ce:link id="lk0050" locator="mmc2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/46.1" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/mmc2"/>
                        </ce:e-component>
                     </ce:display>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:e-component id="ec0015">
                           <ce:label>Table S2</ce:label>
                           <ce:caption id="cap0080">
                              <ce:simple-para id="sp0115" view="all">Standardized ring-width chronologies and sample depths for <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> at 47 locations across its native range. Locations listed from north to south and correspond with <ce:cross-ref id="cr0810" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                                 <ce:bold>,</ce:bold> 
                                 <ce:cross-ref id="cr0815" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>, and <ce:bold>Fig. S1</ce:bold>. Tree-level chronologies, which include series dated with high confidence and ≥ 30 yr in length, are detrended with 32-yr spline. Standard versions of tree-level chronologies are combined to generate location chronologies with no further detrending. All years are listed for chronologies even when replication and signal strength decline (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0820" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0825" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:simple-para>
                           </ce:caption>
                           <ce:link id="lk0055" locator="mmc3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/46.1" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/mmc3"/>
                        </ce:e-component>
                     </ce:display>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:e-component id="ec0020">
                           <ce:label>Table S3</ce:label>
                           <ce:caption id="cap0085">
                              <ce:simple-para id="sp0120" view="all">Standardized ring-width chronologies and tree replication for <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> in two regions and four sub-regions. Northern region is north of 40° N, and southern region is south of the San Francisco Peninsula. Northern sub-regions are 40–41° and 41–42°. Southern sub-regions are Santa Cruz Mountains and northern Santa Lucia Mountains. Trees from primary forests in each region or sub-region are used to generate chronologies. Tree-level chronologies, generated using all series dated with high confidence and ≥ 30 yr in length, are detrended with a 32-yr spline. Standard versions of tree-level chronologies are combined to generate regional chronologies with no further detrending. Chronologies correspond to <ce:cross-ref id="cr0830" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                                 <ce:bold>c</ce:bold>.</ce:simple-para>
                           </ce:caption>
                           <ce:link id="lk0060" locator="mmc4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/46.1" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/mmc4"/>
                        </ce:e-component>
                     </ce:display>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:e-component id="ec0025">
                           <ce:label>Fig. S1</ce:label>
                           <ce:caption id="cap0090">
                              <ce:simple-para id="sp0125" view="all">Standardized ring-width chronologies and sample depths for <ce:italic>Sequoia sempervirens</ce:italic> at 47 locations distributed across its native range. Blue lines show standard version of chronologies sequenced from north to south. Location number in upper left corresponds to <ce:cross-ref id="cr0835" refid="tbl0010">Table 2</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0840" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>. For each tree, series dated with high confidence and ≥ 30 yr are detrended with a 32-year spline. Standard versions of tree chronologies are used in location chronologies with no further detrending. Dotted lines show all series sampled, solid lines show series used in chronologies, and thicker gray lines show tree replication. Refer to <ce:cross-ref id="cr0845" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref> for signal strength.</ce:simple-para>
                           </ce:caption>
                           <ce:link id="lk0065" locator="mmc5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1125786523000139/mmc5"/>
                        </ce:e-component>
                     </ce:display>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:appendices>
